 Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Oliver","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French name, <i>Olivier</i>, recorded as the name of one of Charlemagne's paladins (retainers), the close companion in arms of Roland in the Chanson de Roland. Whereas Roland is headstrong and rash, Oliver is thoughtful and cautious. Ostensibly this name derives from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i> ‘olive tree’ (  compare  Olive  ), but Charlemagne's other paladins all bear solidly Germanic names, so it is more probably an altered form of a Germanic name, perhaps distantly connected with Old Norse <i>Óleifr</i> ‘ancestral relic’. It has remained in more or less continuous use since the medieval period, becoming ever more popular since the 1980s."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Oliver de Eyncourt was born in 1150, in Blankney, Lincolnshire, England, his father, John de Eyncourt, was 19 and his mother, Alice Murdac, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Lady Amabel de Plesley. He died in 1201, in his hometown, at the age of 51, and was buried in Bottesford, Leicestershire, England."},"et":{"1150–1201":"1150–1201","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1154–